\subsection{The amanuensis planning sheet}

Unlike the time report, here we do \emph{not} compute the percentage of full
time ourselves and write it in.  The department's template already contains the
formulas for \enquote{\foreignlanguage{swedish}{Summa timmar}} and
\enquote{\foreignlanguage{swedish}{Procent av helår}}, and HR trusts those
formulas.  Our job is only to supply the input numbers --- the per-course hours
and coefficients --- and let the template recompute.  As long as we fill the
inputs so that each row's hour formula reproduces our own
\enquote{\foreignlanguage{swedish}{omräknad tid}}, the sheet's percentage agrees
with what [[compute_amanuensis_data]] reports.  This is why every coordinate is
a named constant (see \cref{TemplateCellMap}): the day the department revises
the template, we remap constants instead of hunting literals.

<<functions>>=
def make_amanuensis_xlsx(name, email, start, end, course_rows,
                         responsible=("", ""), output=None):
    """Generate an amanuensis planning spreadsheet from a template.

    Fills the department's planning template with course data while preserving
    all formulas. The template's Summa timmar and Procent av helår formulas
    will recompute the same totals our own functions produce.

    Args:
        name: Name of the amanuensis
        email: Email of the amanuensis
        start: Employment start date (datetime.date)
        end: Employment end date (datetime.date)
        course_rows: List of per-course dicts with keys:
            kurskod, avdelning, period, ovn_koeff, ovn_tim,
            gruppansvar, labb_koeff, labb_tim, mote, rattning, ovrigt
        responsible: Tuple of (name, email) for responsible teacher
        output: Output filename (default: generated from name and timestamp)
    """
    <<set default output filename>>
    <<cap course rows at the template's eight>>
    <<load the planning template from the package>>
    <<clear the example course rows>>
    <<write the amanuensis and period header>>
    <<write one input row per course>>
    wb.save(output)
@

When the caller gives no filename we name the file after the amanuensis and the
moment of generation, so repeated runs do not clobber each other and the file
sorts chronologically.

<<set default output filename>>=
if output is None:
    output = f"{name}-{datetime.datetime.now():%Y-%m-%dT%H%M%S}.xlsx"
@

The template has a fixed number of data rows, and the
\enquote{\foreignlanguage{swedish}{Summa timmar}} total sums exactly that
range.  We therefore cap the courses \emph{before} writing any of them: rows
written past the range would be silently excluded from the total --- a wrong
percentage is worse than a logged warning about a truncated list.

<<cap course rows at the template's eight>>=
if len(course_rows) > MAX_COURSE_ROWS:
    logging.warning(
        f"Amanuensis {name} has {len(course_rows)} courses, "
        f"but template only supports {MAX_COURSE_ROWS}. "
        f"Truncating to first {MAX_COURSE_ROWS} courses."
    )
    course_rows = course_rows[:MAX_COURSE_ROWS]
@

We read the template from the installed package rather than a path on disk, so
it works from a wheel; this is the same [[pkgutil.get_data]] idiom the logo
uses.

<<load the planning template from the package>>=
wb = load_workbook(io.BytesIO(pkgutil.get_data(__name__, TEMPLATE_FILE)))
ws = wb[TEMPLATE_SHEET]
@

The shipped template carries an example amanuensis in its data rows.  We blank
every \emph{input} cell across all data rows before filling, but deliberately
never touch the formula cells --- clearing those would defeat the entire
purpose of using the template.

<<clear the example course rows>>=
for row_idx in range(FIRST_COURSE_ROW, FIRST_COURSE_ROW + MAX_COURSE_ROWS):
    for col in COURSE_COLUMNS.values():
        ws[f"{col}{row_idx}"] = None
@

The header identifies the amanuensis and the employment period.  The number of
days and the percentage are template formulas derived from the period dates, so
we write only the dates and leave those cells alone.

<<write the amanuensis and period header>>=
ws[AMANUENSIS_NAME_CELL] = name
ws[AMANUENSIS_EMAIL_CELL] = email
ws[RESPONSIBLE_NAME_CELL] = responsible[0]
ws[RESPONSIBLE_EMAIL_CELL] = responsible[1]
ws[PERIOD_START_CELL] = start
ws[PERIOD_END_CELL] = end
@

Each course becomes one data row.  We map dict keys to columns through
[[COURSE_COLUMNS]] and skip keys a particular row omits, leaving those cells
blank rather than guessing a value.

<<write one input row per course>>=
for i, course in enumerate(course_rows):
    row_idx = FIRST_COURSE_ROW + i
    for key, col in COURSE_COLUMNS.items():
        if key in course:
            ws[f"{col}{row_idx}"] = course[key]
@

\subsection{The template cell map}\label{TemplateCellMap}

Every coordinate the planning generator touches lives here, named for what it
holds.  Collecting them in one place is what lets the generator above read as
intent (\enquote{write the period start}) rather than spreadsheet trivia, and
it makes a future template revision a single edit.  [[COURSE_COLUMNS]] maps a
course-row key to its column; the rows themselves run from [[FIRST_COURSE_ROW]]
for [[MAX_COURSE_ROWS]] rows.

<<constants>>=
TEMPLATE_FILE = "Mall_amanuenser_ht2025.xlsx"
TEMPLATE_SHEET = "EXEMPEL"

AMANUENSIS_NAME_CELL = "D6"
AMANUENSIS_EMAIL_CELL = "J6"
RESPONSIBLE_NAME_CELL = "D8"
RESPONSIBLE_EMAIL_CELL = "J8"
PERIOD_START_CELL = "D10"
PERIOD_END_CELL = "G10"

FIRST_COURSE_ROW = 26
MAX_COURSE_ROWS = 8

COURSE_COLUMNS = {
    "kurskod": "C",
    "avdelning": "D",
    "period": "E",
    "ovn_koeff": "G",
    "ovn_tim": "H",
    "gruppansvar": "I",
    "labb_koeff": "K",
    "labb_tim": "L",
    "mote": "N",
    "rattning": "O",
    "ovrigt": "P",
    "responsible": "U"
}
@

The defining property of this generator is that it writes \emph{only} inputs
and leaves the formulas to do the arithmetic.  We verify both halves: the
formula cells still hold formulas (and still reference the input cells we
wrote), and the input cells hold the numbers we passed.

<<test functions>>=
def test_make_amanuensis_xlsx_formula_preservation(tmp_path):
    """Test that make_amanuensis_xlsx preserves template formulas."""
    from openpyxl import load_workbook

    course_rows = [
        {
            "kurskod": "DD1310",
            "avdelning": "TCS",
            "period": "1",
            "ovn_koeff": 2.0,
            "ovn_tim": 10.0,
            "gruppansvar": 0,
            "labb_koeff": 1.5,
            "labb_tim": 5.0,
            "mote": 2.0,
            "rattning": 3.0,
            "ovrigt": 1.0,
        }
    ]

    output_file = tmp_path / "test_amanuensis.xlsx"
    timesheet.make_amanuensis_xlsx(
        name="Test TA",
        email="test@kth.se",
        start=datetime.date(2025, 1, 1),
        end=datetime.date(2025, 6, 30),
        course_rows=course_rows,
        responsible=("Teacher", "teacher@kth.se"),
        output=str(output_file)
    )

    wb = load_workbook(output_file)
    ws = wb["EXEMPEL"]

    # Formula cells must still hold formulas, and the hours formula must
    # still depend on the input cells we wrote (that is what makes the
    # spreadsheet reproduce our totals).
    assert str(ws["Q26"].value).startswith("=")
    assert "H26" in str(ws["Q26"].value)
    assert str(ws["R26"].value).startswith("=")
    assert str(ws["D12"].value).startswith("=")

    # Input cells must hold exactly the numbers we passed.
    assert ws["C26"].value == "DD1310"
    assert ws["D26"].value == "TCS"
    assert ws["E26"].value == "1"
    assert ws["G26"].value == 2.0
    assert ws["H26"].value == 10.0
@

